<a name="permissions-needed"></a>

## Permissions Needed

<a name="launch-permissions"></a>

### Launch Permissions
- “INTERNET”
- “ACCESS_NETWORK_STATE” (Amazon)
- “WAKE_LOCK”
- “INSTALL_SHORTCUT”
- “RECEIVE_BOOT_COMPLETED”
   - Important. Required for proper functioning of reminders.
- “VIBRATE”
   - Optional. You may remove it using tools:node if you don’t have it already
<br />

<a name="staggered-permissions"></a>

### Staggered Permissions
 - “RECEIVE_SMS”
 - “READ_SMS”
 - “ACCESS_FINE_LOCATION”
 - “WRITE_EXTERNAL_STORAGE”
 - “GET_ACCOUNTS”
 - “READ_PHONE_STATE”
    - Only mandatory if you’re using our referral system (remove otherwise)  
    <br />

<a name="remove-these-permissions-if-you-are-not-using-them-already"></a>

### Remove these permissions (if you’re not using them already)  
Permissions also gets merged from library dependencies which our SDK has, so in that case some permissions are optional/removable if not being used by your app already.  
To remove a permission, mention **uses-permission** with node value as “remove”  
For e.g.

```xml
<uses-permission android:name="<PERMISSION_NAME>" tools:node="remove"/>
```
  - “USE_CREDENTIALS”
  - “AUTHENTICATE_ACCOUNTS”


<a name="manifest-meta-data"></a>

## Manifest Meta Data
The following meta-data needs to be added to the manifest file. Note the use **“android:resource”** in first three meta-data here, which requires you to put actual value in a string resource.

```xml
<meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.ApiKey"
    android:resource="@string/haptik_sdk_api_key"/>
<meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.BaseUrl"
    android:resource="@string/haptik_sdk_base_url"/>
<meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.ClientId"
    android:resource="@string/haptik_sdk_client_id"/>
<meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.NotificationIconSmall"
    android:resource="@drawable/ic_notification_small"/>
<meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.NotificationIconLarge"
    android:resource="@drawable/ic_notification_large"/>
```

Add string resources like below which you’ll be referencing above

```xml
<string name="haptik_sdk_client_id">CLIENT ID will be provided by Haptik </string>
<string name="haptik_sdk_api_key">API KEY will be provided by Haptik </string>
<string name="haptik_sdk_base_url">BASE URL will be provided by Haptik </string>
```
Below two are meta-data for our analytics platform’s (CleverTap) authorization.
```xml
<meta-data android:name="CLEVERTAP_ACCOUNT_ID"  
     android:value="<Will be provided by Haptik>"/>  
<meta-data android:name="CLEVERTAP_TOKEN"
    android:value="<Will be provided by Haptik>"/>
```  

If in case, your app doesn’t want to add haptik specific meta-data through manifest then HaptikLib provides setter method for all of them. Just make sure that you set all of them before calling HaptikLib.init() so that everything gets initialized properly. Also there is a method which allows to set notification icon per business/channel. So you may use that functionality depending on your product requirements.

For SSO SDK to work, you'll need to add the following provider information:

```
<!-- Please don't use string resources here as it will not work  -->
<provider android:name="com.login.nativesso.provider.TgidSaver"
    android:authorities="androidcontentprovidersso.tg.UNIQUE_CUSTOM_SUFFIX"
    android:exported="true" />
```

Here are the details for updating the above information and creating the `UNIQUE_CUSTOM_SUFFIX`:

- `androidcontentprovidersso.tg` is constant prefix.
- After the prefix, give a specific name identifier for your app.
- `UNIQUE_CUSTOM_SUFFIX` should be **unique** otherwise app will not install on the device due to common authority name.
- For example, if your package name is com.abc.xyz, use COM\_ABC\_XYZ as `UNIQUE_CUSTOM_SUFFIX`.

This way `android:authorities` will look like:

 ```
 androidcontentprovidersso.tg.COM_ABC_XYZ
 ```

 Once the provider configuration is set, you'll need to add a meta-data for the same:

 ```
 <!-- For SSO initialization -->
 <meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.SsoProviderAuthority"
    android:value="androidcontentprovidersso.tg.UNIQUE_CUSTOM_SUFFIX" />
 ```
<a name="manifest-entries-for-activities"></a>

## Manifest Entries for Activities

The following Activity needs to be added to your Manifest. Adding a parent will make sure that the UP button in the ChatActivity will take the user to the correct activity. If you implement an Activity which will host the InboxView then that would be the ideal candidate to be the parent of the ChatActivity.
```xml
<activity android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.messaging.ChatActivity" android:parentActivityName="ENTER THE ACTIVITY YOU WANT AS THE PARENT HERE">
    <meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.messaging.backAsUp" android:value="true"/>
</activity>
```

The meta-data tag which is part of the ChatActivity is used to define the behaviour of the back button when the user is in the ChatActivity. There are two possible behaviours that can be assigned to the back button:  
 - The back button will behave the same way as the up button  
 - The back button will follow the default Android behaviour of a back button.  

For the first option the **value** field needs to be set to true and for the second option it needs to
be set to false. Incase you don’t add this meta-data tag the value is set to true.

First of all, you need to do maven repository setup in your root ` build.gradle ` for our sdk, and
some of our internal dependencies.
For Haptik SDK
```java
maven {
    url "http://artifactory.hellohaptik.com:8081/artifactory/libs-release-local"  

    credentials {
        username "<ASK HAPTIK FOR USERNAME>"  
        password "<ASK HAPTIK FOR PASSWORD>"  
    }  
}
```

<a name="sdk-dependencies-setup"></a>

## SDK Dependencies Setup

First of all, you need to do maven repository setup in your root ` build.gradle ` for our sdk, and
some of our internal dependencies.
For Haptik SDK
```java
maven {
    url "http://artifactory.hellohaptik.com:8081/artifactory/libs-release-local"
    credentials {
        username "<ASK HAPTIK FOR USERNAME>"
        password "<ASK HAPTIK FOR PASSWORD>"
    }
}
```

After this add Haptik’s dependency as below,

 - Haptik SDK without cab functionality
```java
compile 'ai.haptik.android.sdk:haptiklib-core:4.1.0-41180'
```
 - Haptik SDK with cab functionality  
```java
compile 'ai.haptik.android.sdk:haptiklib-cab:4.1.0-41180'
```
 - Haptik SDK with payment  
```java
compile 'ai.haptik.android.sdk:haptiklib-payment:4.1.0-41180'
```

**For TIL SDK**
```java
maven {
    url "http://tilsdk.indiatimes.com/nexus/content/groups/public/"
}
```

**For PhonePe SDK**
 - For phonePe, you first need to send us your app’s SHA id, as phonePe requires it to generate a password for particular app.
 - If your app has different SHA for debug and production versions, then please send both SHA separately, and you’ll be given two passwords one for each.
 - Then add below maven setup for PhonePe   
```java
maven {
    url "http://phonepe.bintray.com/PhonePeThinAndroidSDK"
    credentials {
        username 'phonepe_android_thinsdk_release_key@phonepe'
        password '<ASK HAPTIK FOR PASSWORD>'
    }
}
```

**Conflict Resolution**  
It's possible that SDK and the Host app specify common dependencies, which might result in
compile failure on the grounds of class duplication. In such cases specify resolutionStrategy on
your App's build.gradle as follows:
```java
configurations . all {
    resolutionStrategy {
        force < path to your version of conflicting library - 1>
        force < path to your version of conflicting library - 2>
    }
}
```
<a name="first-launch--initialization"></a>

## First Launch / Initialization
Make sure you have followed the previous steps of updating your manifest and setting up the relevant dependencies.

The SDK needs to be checked initialization and needs to be initialized in 2 main places

- **Before utilizing any Haptik functionality**  
  - HaptikLib.init() must be called before using any library functionality such as opening the Inbox View or Messaging.  This may or may not be in the Application Class. **It is recommended to call the init() function in the Application class for the best user experience.**  
  - performInitialDataSync() must be called the first time Haptik is started, before signup. This is a network call and will require 4 to 5 seconds the first time.  

Please refer to the javadocs for more details on their callbacks and parameters.  


- **On receiving push notifications**  
  - HaptikLib.init() must be called if it’s not initialized already before handing the FCM payload to the Haptik’s Notification Manager

<a name="push-notifications"></a>

## Push Notifications
Make sure you provide your main activity reference via below method. It’s strongly recommended to call this from Application class, as it would be needed to be used in every app runtime
```
// Here ClientActivity is the activity of home screen of client app
HaptikLib.setClientMainActivityClass(ClientActivity.class);
```
<a name="push-listener"></a>

### Push Notification Listener

For FCM, pass any payloads from your FCMMessagingService to the Haptik Notification Manager
```java
    final Map<String, String> data = remoteMessage.getData();
    if (HaptikNotificationManager.isHaptikNotification(data)) {
        if (!HaptikLib.isInitialized()) {
            Handler mainHandler = new Handler(getApplicationContext().getMainLooper());
            mainHandler.post(new Runnable() {
                @Override
                public void run() {
                    HaptikLib.init(Utils.getHaptikInitData(getApplication()));
                    HaptikNotificationManager.handleNotification(getApplicationContext(), data);
                }
            });
        } else {
            HaptikNotificationManager.handleNotification(getApplicationContext(), data);
        }
    }
```

For GCM, pass any payloads from your GCMMessagingService to the Haptik Notification Manager
```java
    if (HaptikNotificationManager.isHaptikNotification(bundle)) {
         if (!HaptikLib.isInitialized()) {
             HaptikLib.init((AppApplication) getApplicationContext());
         }
         HaptikNotificationManager.handleNotification(getApplicationContext(), bundle);
     }
```
<a name="push-token-registration"></a>

### Token Registration

Set the Device Token on the Haptik Library
```java
// For FCM use
HaptikLib.setFcmDeviceToken(this, refreshedToken);
    
// For GCM use
HaptikLib.setGcmDeviceToken(this, refreshedToken);
```
   
Enables or disables notification (probably being triggered from your app settings).

```java
Haptik.setNotificationEnabled(boolean enabled) // default is true
```

<a name="user-authentication"></a>

## User Authentication
#### User Signup Types
User Registration and signup can be performed with any one of the following 3 authentication types  
1.	BASIC  
2.	TOI_SSO  
3.	OTP  
4.	THIRD_PARTY
5.  IIFL

Basic Authentication is a guest form of signup that does not require any sort of server-server/ 3rd party verification. This is ideal for chat bots that are either informational in nature or where user identity is handled by a 3rd party provider(Facebook, Twitter etc)

The following parameter is required while signing up with **BASIC** authType:

 - *Optional*: Name

Although name is optional, but it is **recommended** to provide user's name as it does help in customizing user experience.

TOI_SSO, THIRD_PARTY and OTP authentication types are verification types where User’s phone number will be validated from the Haptik Backend via a client API for additional security before Haptik account and wallet creation.

For TrueCaller login you need TrueCaller SDK `aar` file and PartnerKey. You will get PartnerKey for your app from TrueCaller developer console and need to add it in your `AndroidManifest.xml`. Please find the example below :
```java
    <meta-data android:name="com.truecaller.android.sdk.PartnerKey" android:value="@strings/YOUR_TRUECALLER_PARTNER_KEY"/>
```

To add AAR file, go to AndroidStudio's File menu :
New -> New Module -> Select Import AAR/JAR Package option -> Select the provided TrueCaller SDK AAR file.

The following parameters are required while signing up with **TOI_SSO** authType on top of what is required for **BASIC** authType:

 - *Mandatory*: OTP Verified Mobile Number
 - *Mandatory*: Token/TicketId for OTP verification (for 3-way handshake, creation of Wallet)
 - *Optional*: Resident City

**NOTE** that city name **MUST** be either one of the cities mentioned on Haptik SDK or provide “Other” as a String. Values as array resources can be found at `ai.haptik.android.sdk.R.array.cityArray`

The following parameters are required while signing up with **OTP** authType on top of what is required for TOI_SSO authType:

 - *Optional*: Email (unverified is OK)

The following parameters are required while signing up with **IIFL** authType on top of what is required for **BASIC** authType:

 - *Mandatory*: Auth ID
 - *Mandatory*: Token/TicketId for verification

### Update user token 
If you are using token based auth system, then you may want to update user token of logged in user. You can update user token by using `HaptikLib.updateUserToken()` method. For this you need to save `auth_id` and `auth_type` of logged in user in your local cache. Eg: Shared Preferences or Local Database.

```
HaptikLib.updateUserToken(new_token, auth_id, auth_type, new Callback<Boolean>() {
    @Override
    public void success(Boolean result) {
        // handle response
    }
    
    @Override
    public void failure(HaptikException exception) {
        // handle response
    }
});
```

<a name="integrating-the-progress-view"></a>

### Integrating the HaptikSignupProgress View
This custom view takes care of showing progress in the UI while the user is signing up on Haptik SDK.

The view takes custom styleable-attributes individually to display the titles and subtitles. If attributes are not specified in xml, the default values of the titles and subtitles are used in implementation. 
The UI contains following components: 

- **Titles**: If more than one available, they are switched using animation. 
- **Subtitles**: If more than one available, they are switched using animation.

The **length** of both the title and subtitle arrays needs to be same, else the **default values** will be used.

It is **highly recommended** to show this view while user is signing up on Haptik SDK to make a smooth user experience.

Please look at API reference of InboxView in **javadocs** and the **Haptik SDK Demo** app regarding how to integrate this view.

<a name="opening-haptik"></a>

### TIL SSO Specific signUp method
To make the signUp call easier regarding TIL SSO integration,
We have added a method called `signUpViaSso()` in `HaptikLib.java`.

This method internally will take care of checking whether this user is already signed up in parent app on device via TIL SSO or not. If user is found then SDK will automatically sign that user up on Haptik, otherwise user will be signed in as a guest user.

If you're using TIL SSO, then you may use,

`HaptikLib.signUpViaSso()` instead of
`HaptikLib.signUp()`

## Opening Haptik
Before opening any of the Haptik Views, make sure the Library has been initialized, initial data sync has been done and user has successfully signed in.

<a name="integrating-the-inbox-view"></a>

### Integrating the Inbox View
A haptik view which takes care of showing banners and the channels list in the UI. Takes custom styleable-attributes individually to decide whether to show banner or not. If attributes are not specified in xml, the default implementation assumes false for these values

Please look at API reference of InboxView in javadocs regarding how to integrate Inbox

<a name="opening-messaging-view-directly"></a>

### Opening Messaging View Directly
Ability to open haptik activity for the Messaging View directly. To be initialized with the unique business name of the channel that you wish to open the Messaging Activity for.

Ask Haptik for mapping of business to their unique name which you may then utilize in SDK
```java
// Opens messaging/chat view of specified channel
Router.launchChannel(Context context, String channelViaName);
```

<a name="analytics"></a>

## Analytics
We provide `AnalyticsCallback` class which has various methods which gets triggered on various scenarios.

One important method is `logEvent(String, Map<String, Object>)`. This method gets called on every analytics event which gets triggered from SDK.

**Example usage of this method,**

_If you want to track when user gets through OTP based signup process after initially signing up as a guest user, then you may track that in this callback method._

_EventName for that event is --> `OTP_Verification_Completed`_

<a name="running-test-environment"></a>

## Running Test Environment
Set run environment to staging if running build with non-production credentials. Default environment is production. Failing to set this method would end up in feature/functionality failure during runtime. It’s strongly recommended to call this from Application class of the app.

```java
HaptikLib.setRunEnvironment(HaptikLib.RUN_ENVIRONMENT_STAGING);
```

<a name="wallet-information-screen"></a>

## Wallet Information Screen
SDK has an inbuilt wallet information screen which has two tabs:

1. To View Wallet Balance 
2. To see wallet history

Router class provides two methods to launch wallet information screen,
```java
// Opens wallet information screen with wallet balance tab opened
Router.showWallet(Activity callingActivity);

// Opens wallet information screen with wallet history tab opened
Router.showWalletHistory(Activity callingActivity);
```

<a name="addeditdeleteretrieve-user-addresses"></a>

## Add/Edit/Delete/Retrieve User Address(es)
SDK provides ways to allow user to add, retrieve or delete address which client can utilize if they would like. Internally in Haptik flow, it gets used where we need confirm address from user which we then save into database along with a tagname for each address.
```java
// Opens inbuilt UI which allows user to provide and save address
Router.addAddress(Activity callingActivity);

// Opens inbuilt UI which allows user to edit provided address and then save updates
Router.editAddress(Activity callingActivity, Address address);
```
Mainly only above two methods should be sufficient for most use cases, but SDK also provides a helper class called AddressHelper which provides utility methods as mentioned below,
```java
// Add a constructed address object directly without going through UI
AddressHelper.addAddress();
// Delete an address
AddressHelper.deleteAddress();
// Get List of address
AddressHelper.getAddresses();
// Get List of address in async fashion via callback
AddressHelper.getAddressesAsync();
```

## Style Guide


<a name="font-and-color-guide"></a>

### Font and Color Guide
 - Define color values in your resources with given names via a hex value
 - Use tools:override="true" if you have also defined a color with same name
 - Check below design guidelines documentation for more detailed information, https://docs.google.com/a/haptik.co/document/d/1V8sX9AbMU59YlBEmh4wPFVCQR3dcpbQIZAhC1l9OHOY/edit?usp=sharing

### Custom Typography
 - Put font per style in the assets folder and then provide font name as the string resource. For example, “Regular” (we set the path and also the extension at the end)
 - Check provided design documentation for more detailed information regarding which font style is being used where.

| Font String resource name	 | Font value Example |
|--------|
| haptik_font_regular |	Regular |
| haptik_font_medium |	Medium |
| haptik_font_light |	Light |



<a name="share-functionality"></a>

## Share Functionality
SDK provides inbuilt share functionality where user share the app with others via social media apps or any other medium through a custom BottomSheet Layout.

When user shares something, a custom content message gets shared.

Client can override this message with their own custom content along with their deeplink URL

To override the default message, add two string resources exactly named as,
```xml
<string name="haptik_share_text">[Your custom Message>]. Check out this great app %s</string>
<string name="haptik_share_link">[Your Share Link]</string>
```

<a name="multiple-clevertap-account-issue"></a>

## Multiple CleverTap Account Issue
If you're already using `CleverTap` SDK in your app and sending analytic events then there might be potential issue where `CleverTap` can't support two different accounts' events getting fired from one app.

In this case, you may disable `CleverTap` functionality from `Haptik SDK` by setting this `meta-data` property in your manifest.

```xml
<meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.EnableCleverTap"
        android:value="false" />
```

<a name="migration-from-earlier-versions"></a>

## Migration From Earlier Versions


<a name="moving-from-210---220"></a>

### Moving from 2.1.0 -> 2.2.0
**HaptikLib.init()** has been changed to take an Application reference in the argument
**HaptikLib.setDeviceToken(String)** now required a Context in the argument as well
**HaptikLib.setActivityLifecycleCallback(Application)** has been removed  
**ErrorType** ERROR_LIFECYCLE_CALLBACKS_NOT_SET has been removed from HaptikException

### Moving from 2.6.0 -> 2.9.0
Update following dependencies in your app’s build.gradle,
```java
compile 'org.eclipse.paho:org.eclipse.paho.client.mqttv3:1.2.0'
```

PhonePe support has been added in our SDK. Make sure you follow the steps mentioned below for it to work properly.

Add following dependencies in your root build.gradle’s repositories block,
```java
maven {
   url "http://phonepe.bintray.com/PhonePeThinAndroidSDK"
   credentials {
       username 'Ask Haptik'
       password 'Ask Haptik'
   }
}
```

Add following dependencies in your app’s build.gradle,

```java
compile 'phonepe.thinsdk.android.release:merchantsdk:0.3.2'
```

For security purpose, PhonePe requires the SHA-1(which you will need to provide us) of your app’s production and debug keystore(if both are different) to generate the PhonePe-ID for your app.
Once we get the SHA-1, PhonePe-ID is generated from it and you’ll need to add it as <meta-data> info in AndroidManifest.xml inside <application> tag.

```xml
<meta-data
android:name="com.phonepe.android.sdk.AppId"
android:value="PhonePe-ID" />
```

### Moving from 2.9.0 -> 2.10.0
- Haptik SDK is now distributed as a gradle dependency! So make sure you add our private maven repo in your app’s root build.gradle.

```css
maven {
   url "http://artifactory.hellohaptik.com:8081/artifactory/libs-release-local"
   credentials {
       username "{ASK HAPTIK FOR USERNAME}"
       password "{ASK HAPTIK FOR PASSWORD}"
   }
}
```
- After this add Haptik’s dependency as below,

Haptik SDK without cab functionality
```java
compile 'ai.haptik.android.sdk:haptiklib-core:2.10.0-30146'
```

Haptik SDK with cab functionality
```java
compile 'ai.haptik.android.sdk:haptiklib-cab:2.10.0-30146'
```

- You may remove all haptik related maven based dependencies except AmazonPay since it’s standalone AAR based

- If you're using our `cab` functionality/sdk then you would now need to enable it programmatically. Make sure to add this line just anytime before or just after you call HaptikLib.init()

```java
HaptikLib.setApis(CabApiFactory.getCabApi());
```

<a name="moving-from-2100---300"></a>
### Moving from 2.10.0 -> 3.0.0
- This release adds more modularity to Haptik SDK by introducing payments as separate module. From now onwards, payments is not a part of `core` module.

- Add the following dependency for using payment module,

Haptik SDK with payment functionality
```java
compile 'ai.haptik.android.sdk:haptiklib-payment:3.0.0-30150'
```

- Please DO NOT remove AmazonPay dependency as it's standalone AAR, and not a maven dependency, if you are using payment.

- init function of HaptikLib has got signature changes, so it will break dependent app compilation. New InitData has been introduced along with a Builder. Please check the below example:

```java
InitData initData = new InitData.Builder(this)
   .baseUrl(URL)
   .clientMainActivityClass(YourMainActivity.class)
   .apiOptions(CabApiFactory.getCabApi())// For Cabs
   .apiOptions(PaymentApiFactory.getPaymentApi())// For payments
   .debugEnabled(true)// or false, based on build variant
   .notificationSound(R.raw.notification_sound)
   .build();

HaptikLib.init(initData);

```

### Moving from 3.5.0 → 3.6.0
- After this update add Haptik’s dependencies as below,

```java
Haptik core SDK functionality

```


```java
Haptik core SDK with payment functionality
compile 'ai.haptik.android.sdk:haptiklib-payment:3.6.0-36175'
```

- Since SSO SDK is integrated, you'll need to add the below information for it to work:

```
<!-- Please don't use string resources here as it will not work  -->
<provider android:name="com.login.nativesso.provider.TgidSaver"
    android:authorities="androidcontentprovidersso.tg.UNIQUE_CUSTOM_SUFFIX"
    android:exported="true" />
```

Here are the details for updating the above information and creating the `UNIQUE_CUSTOM_SUFFIX`:
- `androidcontentprovidersso.tg` is constant prefix.
- After the prefix, give a specific name identifier for your app.
- `UNIQUE_CUSTOM_SUFFIX` should be **unique** otherwise app will not install on the device due to common authority name.
- For example, if your package name is com.abc.xyz, use COM_ABC_XYZ as `UNIQUE_CUSTOM_SUFFIX`.

This way `android:authorities` will look like:

```
androidcontentprovidersso.tg.COM_ABC_XYZ
```

 Once the provider configuration is set, you'll need to add a meta-data for the same:

```
<!-- For SSO initialization -->
<meta-data android:name="ai.haptik.android.sdk.SsoProviderAuthority"
   android:value="androidcontentprovidersso.tg.UNIQUE_CUSTOM_SUFFIX" />
```
